english:
  title: 'A Teaching on Moral Transformation: A Parting Gift for Kwon Ja-beom'
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ja-beom lost his wife this year. Having served as a Records Official, he petitioned for an external post and was appointed magistrate of Tae-cheon. I went to offer my condolences and asked why he had chosen this path. He replied, "With small children depending on me, I come to Tae-cheon to provide them sustenance. The county is remote and its duties are light, which brings peace to my heart."

    I pressed him further: "With a fifth-rank official's stipend you could not support ten mouths in the capital. How then can a magistrate's lower salary suffice? And how can a remote posting bring the same peace as the clear leisure of an official's life? Yet there is wisdom in your words—we study in youth to practice in maturity. Confined to the capital, one cannot stretch one's limbs; but as magistrate of a county, serving the people directly, one might finally practice what was learned. Perhaps this is why you became magistrate." He assented.

    He then lamented: "What grieves me is that this county lacks worthy people to share in moral transformation."

    I replied: "The purpose of learning is always the welfare of the people. True governance brings strength to the nation. There is no path to this save through moral transformation. Yet common administrators cannot speak of it, and those who understand it often cannot practice it. Why? Only because they despise their age and despise their people. Despise neither, and transformation will flourish. The leader must set the example above; the people respond below. In a village of ten households, there are always the loyal and trustworthy—it is not that people are base. Practice the village feasts and veneration of elders, and your age is not degraded. Confucius thought no less of Wu-cheng and gained Tzu-yu; Han Yu did not look down upon Chao-zhou and gained Chao Te. Why should the people of Tae-cheon be unworthy of your teaching? It depends only on your effort.

    Now, if you seek glory as magistrate to gain higher office later, like the capable administrators of Han—of that I know nothing. But consider: in Song times, Zhou Lianxi and Yang Guishan spent their lives content in county posts. Yet their contentment was not with county life itself, but with practicing what they had learned. If you can share their kind of contentment in Tae-cheon, the people will find their own contentment there—not the petty comfort of mere ease, but something more.

    Moreover, the wise rulers of old always extend themselves to others. Since you have lost a wife, think of the widows and widowers of your county. Since your child has lost its mother's milk, think of the infants waiting for nourishment. With diligent care for their livelihood, then teach them gradually. Proceed from this, and moral transformation shall surely take root."

    Ja-beom said, "Your words are wise." So I write this as my parting gift to you.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhou Lianxi (周濂溪) and Yang Guishan (楊龜山) were Neo-Confucian philosophers of Song dynasty who chose to serve in local posts rather than pursue higher rank, seeing local governance as opportunity to practice their principles.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Confucius and Tzu-yu at Wu-cheng reflects the Analects account where Confucius praised his disciple for transforming the people through moral influence rather than harsh law.
  - key: ''
    value: Han Yu's service in Chao-zhou is a historical example of an official who, despite being sent to a remote region, achieved genuine transformation of the people through sincere commitment to their welfare.
